1245":"1245","1210":"1210","about 1225":"about 1225","February 1245":"February 1245","Saltre Abbey, Stilton, Huntingtonshire, England":"Stilton, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bruce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a place in Normandy, probably from Brix (La Manche).","Altered form of French   Brousse  .","History: The son of the Domesday baron, a friend of David I of Scotland, was granted by him the Lordship of Annandale in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Brousse","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: topographic name for someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Brewis","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Robert De Bruce was born in 1210, in Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, his father, Lord Robert De Bruce, was 35 and his mother, Isabella Ceanmar, was 31. He married Lady Isabel De Huntingdon in 1209, in Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in February 1245, in Huntingdonshire, England, at the age of 35, and was buried in Stilton, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1210–February 1245":"1210–veebruar 1245","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1212–1251":"1212–1251","1225–1295":"1225–1295","1176–1242":"1176–1242","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1242":"1242","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1251":"1251","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1245":"1245","1210":"1210","about 1225":"umbes 1225","February 1245":"veebruar 1245","Saltre Abbey, Stilton, Huntingtonshire, England":"Stilton, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"fi":{"1210–February 1245":"1210–helmikuu 1245","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1212–1251":"1212–1251","1225–1295":"1225–1295","1176–1242":"1176–1242","1179–Female":"1179–Kuollut","1242":"1242","1176":"1176","1295":"1295","1251":"1251","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1245":"1245","1210":"1210","about 1225":"noin 1225","February 1245":"helmikuu 1245","Saltre Abbey, Stilton, Huntingtonshire, England":"Stilton, Huntingdonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Hu